  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 祭文禧公文 代人作
  author: 鄭道傳
  language: lzh
  text: 嗚呼。有昊天之德而不能報。有窮天之憾而不能釋。不肖孤所以痛心而泣血也。而又行高於一世而不能紀。功在於王室而不能白。則不肖孤尤得罪於名敎也。惟我先考。當玄陵潛邸之日。間關萬里。身負羈絏。及王定位。東還于國。入掌樞機。昵侍帷幄。從容參贊。多所裨益。變故相仍。禍亂屢作。不避危險。苦心焦力。以濟艱難。此功在王室者也。間言一入。抽身而出。泥塗其軒冕。弊屣其爵祿。欣然若將終身。無纖芥之形於辭色。至於死生之際。確乎有不可奪之節。其行可謂高於一世矣。自先考之逝。日月倐忽。至十有八年之久。而誌墓之石始刻。不肖孤稽緩之罪。不以是而免也。而先考之行之功。幾泯而復存。豈非幸之萬一哉。卜于吉日。埋此碑石。先考有知。歆我明酌。
korean:
  title: 문희공의 영전에 올리는 제문 남을 대신해서 지은 것이다
  author: 정도전
  language: kor
  text: 아, 슬프다. 선고(先考)께서는 하늘같이 높은 덕이 있었건만, 보답받지 못하였으며, 하늘에 사무치는 한이 있으나, 풀지 못하였으니, 못난 이 아들은 마음 아파 피눈물로 우는 바입니다. 또 선고께서는 행실이 한 세상에 높이 뛰어났건만, 기록되지 못하였으며, 왕실에 공로가 있건만, 밝히지 못하였으니, 못난 아들은 더욱 명교(名敎 인륜의 명분을 밝히는 가르침)에 죄를 지었습니다. 생각하건대, 우리 선고께서는 공민왕(恭愍王)이 잠저(潛邸)에 계실 때, 험하고 가기 어려운 만리 길을 몸소 말고삐를 잡고 호종(扈從)하였다가, 공민왕이 정위(定位)되어 동으로 나라에 돌아오게 되매, 조정에 들어가 추기(樞機)의 정무(政務)를 맡고, 임금을 측근에서 모시면서 종용히 참획(參劃)하고 보필하여 비익(裨益)한 바 많았습니다. 재변과 사고가 서로 잇따르고 병화와 전란이 여러 번 일어났을 때 위험을 무릅쓰고 마음과 힘을 다하여 어려움을 구제하였으니, 이것이 왕실에 공로가 있다는 것입니다. 이간하는 말이 한번 들어가면, 몸을 빼쳐 물러나와 높은 벼슬을 진흙처럼 보고, 그 벼슬과 봉록은 헌신짝처럼 버리면서 흔연(欣然)히 그대로 일생을 마칠 양으로 조금도 말과 얼굴빛에 나타내지 않았으며, 죽고 사는 즈음에 이르러서도 확고하여 빼앗을 수 없는 절개가 있었으니, 그 행실이 한 세상에 높이 뛰어났다고 말할 수 있는 것입니다. 선고께서 돌아가신 때로부터 세월이 훌쩍 지나가서 18년의 장구함에 이르렀습니다. 그리하여 묘를 기록하는 비석을 이제 비로소 새겼습니다. 못난 이 아들의 늦추어 더디게 한 죄를 이것으로써 면할 수는 없습니다만, 선고의 행실과 공로가 거의 민몰(泯沒)할 뻔하다가 다시 세우게 되었으니, 어찌 다행한 일의 만분의 1이라도 되지 않겠습니까. 좋은 날을 가리어, 이 비석을 묻으오니, 아버지시여, 앎이 있으시거든 나의 깨끗한 술잔을 흠향하소서.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1130_010_0010&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: 'Sacrificial Ode to Lord Munhui: Written on Another''s Behalf'
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Alas, sorrowful lament.

    My late father possessed virtue high as heaven itself, yet received no recompense. His heart bore a sorrow too vast for the heavens to contain, yet it remained unresolved. Thus do I, his unworthy son, weep tears of blood, my heart torn asunder.

    Moreover, his conduct stood above all his time, yet went unrecorded. His service to the throne bore fruit, yet his deeds were never made plain. For this, I, his unworthy son, have failed in the sacred duty to illuminate virtue and proper conduct.

    Consider my late father: When the lord dwelt in obscurity during his princely days, he journeyed ten thousand li through mountain passes and perilous roads, bearing chains of exile. When the lord ascended to his rightful position and returned eastward to rule, my father entered the court, took charge of state affairs, stood near the royal seat in intimate counsel, and through measured wisdom contributed greatly to the governance of the realm. When calamities befell us one after another, and rebellion and strife rose repeatedly, he shrank not from danger but exhausted his strength and devoted his soul to rescue the kingdom from distress. Such was his service to the throne.

    Yet when whispers of slander reached his ears, he withdrew himself entirely. He cast aside his rank as one casts off mud from his carriage, discarded his office and stipend like worn-out shoes, and peacefully accepted his retirement as though to spend his days thus unchanged. Not a trace of discontent crossed his lips or showed upon his face. And when death's hour came, his resolve remained unshakeable, a steadfastness that could not be taken from him. Truly, his conduct towered above his generation.

    From the day my father departed, time has flown like a swift shadow. Eighteen years have passed in their entirety. Only now has the stone monument bearing his record been carved. I, his unworthy son, bear the guilt of this prolonged delay, a fault I cannot absolve myself of. Yet the deeds and virtues of my father, which had nearly faded into oblivion, have now been restored to remembrance. Is this not a blessing beyond all measure?

    On this auspicious day, I bury this stone monument. If my father has knowledge of this world, may he accept this pure offering of wine.
  footnotes:
    - The work is a sacrificial ode (祭文) written to accompany the burial of a stone monument recording the deeds of the author's father, Jeong Gwan.
    - '"Potentate in obscurity" (潛邸) refers to the period before King Gongmin formally ascended the throne and consolidated his power.'
    - The eighteen-year interval between the father's death and the erection of the memorial stone likely reflects the turbulent political circumstances of the time, which prevented the proper completion of these duties.
    - The imagery of casting aside rank like mud and office like worn shoes reflects the Confucian ideal of the gentleman who withdraws from politics when his counsel is no longer valued.
